The given probabilities are \( P(A \cup B) = 0.76 \) and \( P(A \cup B') = 0.87 \), and the goal is to find \( P(A) \).

Using the formula for the union of events, \( P(A \cup B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A \cap B) \), and \( P(A \cup B') = P(A) + P(B') - P(A \cap B') \), where \( P(B') = 1 - P(B) \) and \( P(A \cap B') = P(A) - P(A \cap B) \).

Substitute and simplify:
- \( P(A \cup B') = P(A) + (1 - P(B)) - (P(A) - P(A \cap B)) = 1 - P(B) + P(A \cap B) \).
- Given \( P(A \cup B') = 0.87 \), so \( 1 - P(B) + P(A \cap B) = 0.87 \), which simplifies to \( -P(B) + P(A \cap B) = -0.13 \), or \( P(B) - P(A \cap B) = 0.13 \).

Now, from \( P(A \cup B) = 0.76 \):
- \( P(A) + P(B) - P(A \cap B) = 0.76 \).

Substitute \( P(B) - P(A \cap B) = 0.13 \) into the equation:
- \( P(A) + 0.13 = 0.76 \).
- Solving for \( P(A) \), \( P(A) = 0.76 - 0.13 = 0.63 \).

Verification:
- If \( P(A) = 0.63 \) and \( P(B) - P(A \cap B) = 0.13 \), then \( P(A) + P(B) - P(A \cap B) = 0.63 + 0.13 = 0.76 \), which matches \( P(A \cup B) = 0.76 \).
- Also, \( 1 - P(B) + P(A \cap B) = 1 - (P(B) - P(A \cap B)) = 1 - 0.13 = 0.87 \), which matches \( P(A \cup B') = 0.87 \).

The probabilities are consistent, and \( P(A) = 0.63 \) is within the valid range [0, 1].

