The probability that \(X\) exceeds \(Y\) by at least 15 hours is \(P(D \geq 15)\). Standardizing this, the z-score is \(z = \frac{15 - (-50)}{130} = \frac{65}{130} = 0.5\). Thus, \(P(D \geq 15) = P(Z \geq 0.5)\), where \(Z\) is a standard normal variable.

Using the standard normal distribution, \(P(Z \geq 0.5) = 1 - P(Z \leq 0.5)\). From standard normal tables, \(P(Z \leq 0.5) \approx 0.6915\), so \(P(Z \geq 0.5) \approx 1 - 0.6915 = 0.3085\).

The probability is rounded to four decimal places for reasonable significant figures.

