Solution: The ionization energy of H₂ is calculated using the dissociation energies and the ionization energy of the hydrogen atom. The dissociation energy \(D_0(\mathrm{H}_2) = 4.478 \, \mathrm{eV}\) corresponds to \(\mathrm{H}_2 \rightarrow 2\mathrm{H}\), and \(D_0(\mathrm{H}_2^+) = 2.651 \, \mathrm{eV}\) corresponds to \(\mathrm{H}_2^+ \rightarrow \mathrm{H}^+ + \mathrm{H}\). The ionization energy of hydrogen \(\mathrm{H} \rightarrow \mathrm{H}^+ + \mathrm{e}^-\) is \(13.598 \, \mathrm{eV}\).

The ionization energy of \(\mathrm{H}_2\) (IE) is found using the equation:
\[
IE = D_0(\mathrm{H}_2) + IE_{\mathrm{H}} - D_0(\mathrm{H}_2^+)
\]
Substituting the values:
\[
IE = 4.478 + 13.598 - 2.651 = 15.425 \, \mathrm{eV}
\]
