**************
The solution calculates \( D_e \) for \( ^7\text{Li}^1\text{H} \) using the relationship \( D_e = D_0 + \text{ZPE} \), where ZPE is the zero-point energy. The given values are \( D_0 = 2.4287  \text{eV} \), \( \omega_e = 1405.65  \text{cm}^{-1} \), and \( \omega_e x_e = 23.20  \text{cm}^{-1} \).

The ZPE in cm\(^{-1}\) is computed as:
\[
\text{ZPE} = \frac{1}{2} \omega_e - \frac{1}{4} \omega_e x_e = \frac{1}{2} \times 1405.65 - \frac{1}{4} \times 23.20 = 702.825 - 5.80 = 697.025  \text{cm}^{-1}
\]

This is converted to eV using the conversion factor \( 1  \text{cm}^{-1} = 1.239841984 \times 10^{-4}  \text{eV} \):
\[
\text{ZPE}_{\text{eV}} = 697.025 \times 1.239841984 \times 10^{-4} = 0.086420  \text{eV}
\]

Adding to \( D_0 \):
\[
D_e = 2.4287 + 0.086420 = 2.515120  \text{eV}
\]

Rounding to five significant figures, based on the input precisions, gives \( 2.5151  \text{eV} \).

The final answer is $2.5151$.
